      <div xml:id="KT400-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">viṉaimuṟṟi vanta talaimakaṉ ṟērppākaṉait talaiyaḷittatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">HE, who comes after having completed [his] work, showing
          politeness to the charioteer. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT400">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> cēyāṟu cellā māyi ṉiṭariṉṟu</l>
          <l> kaḷaikalaṅ kāmam peruntōṭ keṉṟu</l>
          <l> naṉṟupurin teṇṇiya maṉattai yāki</l>
          <l> murampukaṇ ṇuṭaiya vēkik karampaip</l>
          <l> putuvaḻip paṭutta matiyuṭai valavō</l>
          <l> yiṉṟu tantaṉai tērō</l>
          <l> nōyuḻan tuṟaiviyai nalka lāṉē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l> As one with a mind<note place="foot">What is the significance of <term xml:lang="ta">
            maṉam </term> and <term xml:lang="ta">mati </term> (line 5) here, both of them certainly
            Sanskritisms?</note> , who considered [and] desired what is good:</l>
          <l rend="indent"> “if we don't go the way through the distance without impediment,</l>
          <l rend="indent"> we won't alleviate the desire for [her with]<note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">perum tōḷ </term> can be seen either as a metonymy for HER or for
            HIM, who is desirous of reaching home.</note> big shoulders”,</l>
          <l> you charioteer with a mind that effects new paths</l>
          <l rend="indent"> in the wasteland, setting of to break into<note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">murampu kaṇ</term> : it seems best here to understand <term xml:lang="ta">kaṇ</term> as a locative suffix.</note> mounds of gravel,</l>
          <l> have you given [just] the chariot today?</l>
          <l> With this you are granting<note place="foot">Literally <term xml:lang="ta">nalkalāṉ </term>
            is a verbal noun in the instrumental, which probably is to be understood as a sociative
            (together with).</note> [also] her,</l>
          <l rend="indent6"> who constantly endures pain.<note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">uḻantu uṟaivi</term> : either <term xml:lang="ta">uṟai-tal </term>
            has auxiliary function (see above) or it has to be coordinated "she, who has stayed
            [behind and] endures pain". Against this can be said that uṟaivi is not perfective
            aspect (and "she, who stays" does not seem to make sense in this context).</note></l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
